Patch Set 1:

Don't go to crazy on the unit test.  I'm wondering whether we should just reject the request if no backend is specified.  It might be safer than using the default store.

Patch Set 1:

Punting to the default backend doesn't seem like the right solution to me - e.g. I may have swift as my default backend (for general purpose - user creates and image and wants it stored somewhere), but also have the http store enabled for access to published images.

I wonder if get_size_from_uri_and_backend() could apply the same logic as get() (in glance_store.multi_backend) - i.e. iterate over all backends until it finds one that can handle the scheme and get a size?

Failing that, forcing the specification in the location add request seems like the safest option, although it will break compatibility - it's possible to add a location without specify the backend in current releases, but that will change....

Patch Set 1:

As an experiment / PoC, I added this to glance_store.multi_backend:

def get_backend_for_uri(uri, context=None):
    backends = CONF.enabled_backends
    for backend in backends:
        try:
            if not uri.startswith(backends[backend]):
                continue
            loc = location.get_location_from_uri_and_backend(
                uri, backend, conf=CONF)
            return backend
        except (exceptions.UnknownScheme):
            continue
    raise exceptions.NotFound(_("Scheme cannot be handled by any configured "
                                "backend"))


and this to _do_add_locations() in ImagesController (glance/api/v2/images.py):

        if CONF.enabled_backends and 'backend' not in value['metadata']:
            store = glance_store.get_backend_for_uri(value['url'])
            value['metadata']['backend'] = unicode(store)


and that allows me to add an http location to a queued image, when the default store is a file one, and it correctly picks my http store.

Not sure if it's the right solution, but something to consider....

I have a general concern about this patch.  It was introduced to handle the situation where enabled_backends is set but no store is included in the API request.  It goes well beyond that to duplicating the lazy update of store locations that's already taking place during the image-list call.

I guess you're doing this because at this point in the code, you can't tell a new location from the old ones?

To Iain's point, I think the user-supplied store could be overwritten, but that would be like autocorrect (which may not be what we want to happen when someone is setting/updating locations).  Unless someone tries to configure multiple http stores (which we have decided not to allow).

@Iain: you are the most serious consumer of the http store, do you have any use cases that would be impacted by glance only allowing one http store?

So to get to the point here: (1) I'm worried about the "autocorrect" behavior for bad store names with good URLs; (2) If we have to do the lazy update here (in addition to the image-list call), we need to use a utility function so that the store update code can't get out of sync in multiple places.

My concern wasn't selfish (this time) - I don't think I'd be affected by this change - it just doesn't seem like the right thing to do.
